              encode not only the conscious perception of errors, but also
              their magnitude, in their amplitude and latency. Furthermore, a
              non-linear relationship between the ErrP-BCI output and the
              magnitude of errors predicts individual perceptual thresholds to
              detect rotations. The uncovered relationship is consistent with
              non-human primate studies, which found a similar relationship
              between the size of errors and simple spike activity of Purkinje
              cells, and we conjecture a cerebellar contribution to ErrP. Our
              experimental setup and findings open new avenues to probe and
              extend current theories of performance monitoring, which are
